        "authorId" : "6f6f52c8-bace-4788-98aa-f12fb2560025",
        "body" : "Why this change. Shouldn’t we order alphabetically?",
        "createdAt" : "2019-10-04T20:04:43Z",
        "updatedAt" : "2019-10-04T20:05:15Z",
        "lastEditedBy" : "6f6f52c8-bace-4788-98aa-f12fb2560025",
        "tags" : [
        ]
      },
      {
        "id" : "cd476028-cde2-4a3d-aada-9f8f3d6280fa",
        "parentId" : "5bace3ec-a237-4298-952d-8761c1307b08",
        "authorId" : "e4571402-a12a-4377-8cca-960e88b81e3d",
        "body" : "I always sort includes in logical order - first base class(es), then all others.\r\nAnd base classes listed in order they appears in the code.",
        "createdAt" : "2019-10-04T20:14:22Z",
        "updatedAt" : "2019-10-04T20:14:22Z",
        "lastEditedBy" : "e4571402-a12a-4377-8cca-960e88b81e3d",
        "tags" : [
        ]
      },
      {
        "id" : "0f8f7c8f-535b-4d2d-9df4-2bad2ad9ae10",
        "parentId" : "5bace3ec-a237-4298-952d-8761c1307b08",
        "authorId" : "6f6f52c8-bace-4788-98aa-f12fb2560025",
        "body" : "Doesn’t that presume deep knowledge of the header content? The preprocessor will expand them for you when visiting the transitive includes.\r\n\r\nPS: that’s not very stable because if you move some of the header content elsewhere you should fix all includers, too. \r\n\r\nUsually the common/unwritten rule is by alphabetical order to avoid adding the same header twice and ordered by generality to avoid making headers non-standalone. ",
        "createdAt" : "2019-10-04T20:24:48Z",
        "updatedAt" : "2019-10-04T20:25:49Z",
        "lastEditedBy" : "6f6f52c8-bace-4788-98aa-f12fb2560025",
        "tags" : [
        ]
      },
      {
        "id" : "5807aa52-2211-4d1b-bb3e-451bf1b20b54",
        "parentId" : "5bace3ec-a237-4298-952d-8761c1307b08",
        "authorId" : "e4571402-a12a-4377-8cca-960e88b81e3d",
        "body" : "In 99% of usecases there are few includes in header files. \r\nIn such case alphabetical order does not matter.\r\n",
        "createdAt" : "2019-10-04T20:28:16Z",
        "updatedAt" : "2019-10-04T20:28:16Z",
        "lastEditedBy" : "e4571402-a12a-4377-8cca-960e88b81e3d",
